{{biology-stub}}

'''Auroral kilometric radiation''' ('''AKR''') is the intense radio [[radiation]] emitted in the acceleration zone (at a height of three times the radius of the Earth) of the polar lights. The radiation mainly comes from [[cyclotron radiation]] from [[electrons]] orbiting around the [[magnetic field]] lines of the Earth. The radiation has a [[frequency]] of between 50 and 500&nbsp;kHz and a total [[Power (physics)|power]] of between about 1 million and 10 million [[watt]]s. The radiation is absorbed by the [[ionosphere]] and therefore can only be measured by [[satellites]] positioned at vast heights, such as the [[Fast Auroral Snapshot Explorer (FAST)]]. According to the data of the [[Cluster mission]], it is beamed out in the cosmos in a narrow plane tangent to the magnetic field at the source. The sound produced by playing AKR over an audio device has been described as "whistles", "chirps", and even "screams"{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}.
As some other planets emit cyclotron radiation too, AKR could be used to learn more about [[Jupiter]], [[Saturn]], [[Uranus]] and [[Neptune]], and to detect [[extrasolar planet]]s.
==References== * {{cite web |url=http://sci.esa.int/science-e/www/object/index.cfm?fobjectid=43018 |title=Beamed radio emission from Earth |last=Masson |first=Arnaud |date=2008-06-27 |accessdate=2008-07-01 |publisher=[[European Space Agency|ESA]]}}
