{{notability|Biographies|date=June 2014}}

'''Judith Massare''' is a paleontologist specializing in [[Mesozoic]] [[marine reptile]] research. In [[1987 in paleontology|1987]],  Massare published an analysis of plesiosaur feeding habits. She concluded that the long-necked [[plesiosauroids]] ate soft prey. ''[[Liopleurodon]]'' and its relatives, on the other hand, had teeth resembling those of [[killer whales]] and probably ate larger, bonier prey.<ref name="ellis-pliosaurs-184" /> The next year, Massare analyzed Mesozoic marine reptile swimming abilities and found that long-necked plesiosaurs would have been significantly slower than pliosaurs due to excess drag incurred from their large round bodies.<ref name="ellis-plesiosaurs-152" />

