{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}} {{Use British English|date=April 2015}} {{Infobox award | name = Marcel Benoist Prize | subheader = ''Prix Marcel Benoist'' | current_awards = | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | description = Useful scientific discovery | sponsor = Marcel Benoist Foundation | date = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | location = | country = [[Switzerland]] | presenter = | host = | preshow_host = | acts = | reward = | year = {{Start date and age|1920}} | year2 = | holder = | website = https://marcel-benoist.ch/en/ | runtime = | ratings = | producer = | director = | most_awards = | most_nominations = | image2 = | image2size = | alt2 = | caption2 = | previous = | main = | next = }}
The '''Marcel Benoist Prize''', offered by the '''Marcel Benoist Foundation''', is a monetary prize that has been offered annually since 1920 to a [[scientist]] of [[Switzerland|Swiss]] nationality or residency who has made the most useful scientific discovery. Emphasis is placed on those discoveries affecting human life. Since 1997, candidates in the [[humanities]] have also been eligible for the prize.
The Marcel Benoist Foundation was established by the will of the French lawyer Marcel Benoist, a wartime resident of [[Lausanne]], who died in 1918. It is managed by a group of trustees comprising the Swiss interior minister and heads of the main [[List of universities in Switzerland|Swiss universities]]. It is often dubbed the "Swiss Nobel Prize." <ref>Fabien Goubet, Et la lumière fut téléportée, Le Temps, 28 October 2014</ref> The current laureate is [[Lars-Erik Cederman]].<ref name=snf>{{cite web |author=Swiss National Science Foundation |title=Marcel Benoist Swiss Science Prize is awarded to Lars-Erik Cederman |url=http://www.snf.ch/en/researchinFocus/newsroom/pages/news-180903-lars-eric-cederman-receives-the-benoist-prize.aspx |accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref>
== History ==
The first award was given to [[immunologist]] [[Nicolas Maurice Arthus|Maurice Arthus]] (1862–1945) at the [[University of Lausanne]]. Other winners have included [[computer scientist]] [[Niklaus Wirth]], [[astronomer]] [[Michel Mayor]], and cardiologist [[Max Holzmann]]. {{As of|2003}}, nine Marcel Benoist winners have later also won the [[Nobel Prize]]: Paul Karrer, Walter R. Hess, Leopold Ruzicka, Tadeus Reichstein, Vladimir Prelog, Niels Kaj Jerne, Richard R. Ernst, Johannes G. Bednorz & Karl Alexander Müller, and Kurt Wüthrich.
In 2009, [[Françoise Gisou van der Goot]] ([[École polytechnique fédérale de Lausanne]]) was the first woman to win the Marcel Benoist Prize.
